{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_Aq2y8qgBHtXRU169AEFdxNuz","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Run, judge, and FIX `06-tanzania` — one failure per invocation\n2\t\n3\tYou drive `sdk/org/scenarios/06-tanzania/scenario.yaml` against a LOCAL `lmthing serve`, judge each step on real\n4\tevidence, and when a step fails you fix it at the right layer and PROVE the fix with a fresh rerun.\n5\tYou do this for the FIRST failure only, then stop. You **never commit** — you leave your changes\n6\tuncommitted and write a full report explaining every one; a human reviews and commits to `main`.\n7\t\n8\t<!--\n9\t  scenario-spec.md — the shared foundation for the three scenario prompts (create / extend / judge).\n10\t  It defines what a scenario IS, the file format, the contract every step is judged against, the\n11\t  feature surface to draw from, and the rules that keep authoring honest. create.md, extend.md and\n12\t  judge.md all <!-- include cycle skipped: scenario-spec.md --> this file; it holds no task of its own.\n13\t-->\n14\t\n15\t# What a scenario is\n16\t\n17\tA scenario is a PROMISE a real person makes to themselves — \"get on top of this mess\", \"stop letting\n18\tthings slip\" — played out as a sequence of plain-language messages to THING and judged, on EVERY\n19\tstep, against a set of invariants about what the product must do. It is a story that exercises\n20\tfeatures because a real person's needs demand them — never a feature checklist wearing a persona.\n21\t\n22\tThe judge (a Claude reading the execution trace + the real spaces / DB / knowledge on disk) decides\n23\teach step. So every `expect` must be an OBSERVABLE claim about what the agent DID or what STATE\n24\tchanged — never about the words in its reply. \"The finding lands in the Zanzibar space's knowledge,\n25\twith its source\" is checkable. \"The reply mentions insurance\" passes when the system is broken.\n26\t\n27\t# The file\n28\t\n29\t```\n30\tsdk/org/scenarios/<NN-slug>/\n31\t  scenario.yaml     # persona · promise · invariants · steps (below)\n32\t  fixtures/         # REAL files, each carrying one token found in no other fixture\n33\t  fixtures/links.md # provenance (source URL) for every fixture\n34\t```\n35\t\n36\t`scenario.yaml`:\n37\t\n38\t```yaml\n39\tid:      NN-slug\n40\ttitle:   the promise in a phrase\n41\tproject: the-project-id\n42\t\n43\tpersona: >\n44\t  Who they are, what they already have, what they want — concrete, not generic. A name, a place,\n45\t  real dates, the real objects. They mix languages if the real person would. They never say a\n46\t  product word.\n47\t\n48\tpromise: >\n49\t  The one product claim this story proves or breaks.\n50\t\n51\t# facts the persona can state IF THING asks a legitimate clarifying question (see \"Asking well\").\n52\t# The driver answers everything else in-voice at runtime; this is only for load-bearing answers.\n53\tknows:\n54\t  - \"the permit deposit was cash, 50 euros\"\n55\t\n56\tinvariants:            # judged on EVERY step — pull them verbatim from the library below\n57\t  - IF THE APP SHOWS IT, IT'S A DB ROW ...\n58\t  - ...\n59\t\n60\tsteps:\n61\t  - attach: [file, ...]        # optional: files delivered WITH the message\n62\t    say: \"verbatim user message\"\n63\t    then_say: \"...\"            # optional: a second message in the same step\n64\t    open_app: true             # optional: the user opens the served app\n65\t    in_app_chat: \"...\"         # optional: a message typed INSIDE the app\n66\t    fresh_session: true        # optional: a brand-new session, zero history\n67\t    restart_pod: true          # optional: bounce the pod, assert durability\n68\t    if_asked:                  # optional: steer the persona's answer to an expected question\n69\t      \"remember or remind?\": \"just keep it in mind, don't nag me\"\n70\t    expect:\n71\t      - an observable claim the judge verifies on the trace or on disk\n72\t      - ...\n73\t```\n74\t\n75\t# The person knows ZERO lmthing words (hard rules)\n76\t\n77\t1. They NEVER say — or imply they know — space · project · app · agent · hook · event · webhook ·\n78\t   integration · install · database · table · schema · row · API · build · deploy · function ·\n79\t   capability · consent · delegate · THING. They talk about their life. A message only a docs-reader\n80\t   would write is WRONG — rewrite it."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fecb2053-a7cd-424d-b7dd-79e362aa1cb4","uuid":"d192738f-de75-43ba-9f9b-dae540349693","timestamp":"2026-07-15T18:54:21.096Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/automation/instances/scenario-campaign/rounds/5/06-tanzania/attempt-1/prompt.md","content":"# Run, judge, and FIX `06-tanzania` — one failure per invocation\n\nYou drive `sdk/org/scenarios/06-tanzania/scenario.yaml` against a LOCAL `lmthing serve`, judge each step on real\nevidence, and when a step fails you fix it at the right layer and PROVE the fix with a fresh rerun.\nYou do this for the FIRST failure only, then stop. You **never commit** — you leave your changes\nuncommitted and write a full report explaining every one; a human reviews and commits to `main`.\n\n<!--\n  scenario-spec.md — the shared foundation for the three scenario prompts (create / extend / judge).\n  It defines what a scenario IS, the file format, the contract every step is judged against, the\n  feature surface to draw from, and the rules that keep authoring honest. create.md, extend.md and\n  judge.md all <!-- include cycle skipped: scenario-spec.md --> this file; it holds no task of its own.\n-->\n\n# What a scenario is\n\nA scenario is a PROMISE a real person makes to themselves — \"get on top of this mess\", \"stop letting\nthings slip\" — played out as a sequence of plain-language messages to THING and judged, on EVERY\nstep, against a set of invariants about what the product must do. It is a story that exercises\nfeatures because a real person's needs demand them — never a feature checklist wearing a persona.\n\nThe judge (a Claude reading the execution trace + the real spaces / DB / knowledge on disk) decides\neach step. So every `expect` must be an OBSERVABLE claim about what the agent DID or what STATE\nchanged — never about the words in its reply. \"The finding lands in the Zanzibar space's knowledge,\nwith its source\" is checkable. \"The reply mentions insurance\" passes when the system is broken.\n\n# The file\n\n```\nsdk/org/scenarios/<NN-slug>/\n  scenario.yaml     # persona · promise · invariants · steps (below)\n  fixtures/         # REAL files, each carrying one token found in no other fixture\n  fixtures/links.md # provenance (source URL) for every fixture\n```\n\n`scenario.yaml`:\n\n```yaml\nid:      NN-slug\ntitle:   the promise in a phrase\nproject: the-project-id\n\npersona: >\n  Who they are, what they already have, what they want — concrete, not generic. A name, a place,\n  real dates, the real objects. They mix languages if the real person would. They never say a\n  product word.\n\npromise: >\n  The one product claim this story proves or breaks.\n\n# facts the persona can state IF THING asks a legitimate clarifying question (see \"Asking well\").\n# The driver answers everything else in-voice at runtime; this is only for load-bearing answers.\nknows:\n  - \"the permit deposit was cash, 50 euros\"\n\ninvariants:            # judged on EVERY step — pull them verbatim from the library below\n  - IF THE APP SHOWS IT, IT'S A DB ROW ...\n  - ...\n\nsteps:\n  - attach: [file, ...]        # optional: files delivered WITH the message\n    say: \"verbatim user message\"\n    then_say: \"...\"            # optional: a second message in the same step\n    open_app: true             # optional: the user opens the served app\n    in_app_chat: \"...\"         # optional: a message typed INSIDE the app\n    fresh_session: true        # optional: a brand-new session, zero history\n    restart_pod: true          # optional: bounce the pod, assert durability\n    if_asked:                  # optional: steer the persona's answer to an expected question\n      \"remember or remind?\": \"just keep it in mind, don't nag me\"\n    expect:\n      - an observable claim the judge verifies on the trace or on disk\n      - ...\n```\n\n# The person knows ZERO lmthing words (hard rules)\n\n1. They NEVER say — or imply they know — space · project · app · agent · hook · event · webhook ·\n   integration · install · database · table · schema · row · API · build · deploy · function ·\n   capability · consent · delegate · THING. They talk about their life. A message only a docs-reader\n   would write is WRONG — rewrite it.","numLines":80,"startLine":1,"totalLines":375}}}
